# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: elizabeth-s-gone-raw
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner obtained his M.D. from Yale Medical School in 1909 and received the Campbell Gold Medal for the highest rank on his examination and the Keese Prize for his thesis.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-fleshless-diet] In 1916, Buttner was described by the editor of the *Journal of the American Medical Association* as a "recognized representative in the literature of vegetarianism." He argued for vegetarianism from a scientific basis.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner practiced medicine in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-fleshless-diet] He was a member of the New Haven County Medical Association.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner is best known for his vegetarian book *A Fleshless Diet*, published in 1910.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-fleshless-diet] It was widely reviewed in medical journals with a mixed response.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner argued that comparative anatomy and nutrition demonstrates that man is suited for a fleshless diet and that meat is dangerous and unnecessary.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-fleshless-diet] His recommended diet consisted of vegetables, eggs and milk.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner wrote that "It is not illogical for vegetarians to use milk and eggs, as these animal products are distinctly less toxic than meat and also less likely to be disease-laden.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *American Physical Education Review*, praised the book for compiling useful dietetic research but commented that it failed to show scientific discretion in the selected material.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *Journal of the American Medical Association* recommended the book as a reference work whether or not one accepts Buttner's conclusions.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-fleshless-diet] A review in *The Medical Standard*, noted that the book was a "piece of special pleading for the propaganda which it is designed to promote […] We may say this, however, for Dr.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-sacred-duty] The film opens with footage of a NASA rocket launch, an animation of the Solar System, and a quote from Deuteronomy 30:19 about choosing between life and death (illustrated with images of Earth as seen from space, contrasted with an exploding atom bomb).
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-sacred-duty] This is followed by a statement that humanity has not been caring for the planet properly according to Jewish teachings, which precedes a section about ancient Jewish texts and sacred words that provide "specific instructions on how to be custodians of the world in which we live".
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-sacred-duty] Throughout the film, quotes from the Torah are contrasted with the various environmental threats facing humanity today; the quotes are also illustrated with close-ups of Hebrew scrolls, Jews praying, and scenes of nature.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-sacred-duty] The Earth is again seen from space and the camera moves in to focus on Israel, which the narrator cites as a microcosm of current global problems related to air and water pollution, overpopulation, climate change, and health concerns.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-sacred-duty] The film moves on to look at global problems, with scenes shot all over the world.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-sacred-duty] The focus then shifts to the United States, where all the relevant issues are discussed in detail.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-sacred-duty] Reference is made to *Livestock's Long Shadow*, a 2006 report by the Food and Agriculture Organization which claimed that livestock agriculture produces more greenhouse gases than all of the world's vehicles combined.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-sacred-duty] Next comes a brief presentation, illustrated with simple animated charts, on how meat production is an inefficient way to produce food for a hungry world.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-sacred-duty] This moves into footage of animal abuse on feedlots and in factory farms, and the pollution produced by these facilities.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-sacred-duty] The film then focuses on the advantages of vegetarianism for reducing pollution and solving world hunger.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-sacred-duty] With a change of diet toward vegetarianism, the film asserts that many of these environmental and health problems can be solved.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-sacred-duty] After some fast-moving images of people and nature accompanied by music, the film ends with the same statement from Deuteronomy about "life and death" being narrated over a shot of a sunrise.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-sacred-duty] The idea for the film was inspired by the writings of Richard H.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-sacred-duty] Schwartz (*Judaism and Vegetarianism*, *Judaism and Global Survival*, etc.) who also served as associate producer.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-sacred-duty] Schwartz had seen the Christian Vegetarian Association's 2006 film, *Honoring God's Creation*, and felt that a similar film would be effective in the Jewish community.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-sacred-duty] At the time, he envisioned the film to be about 30 minutes long, though the final film ended up being 60 minutes long.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-sacred-duty] Production began in 2005 with a basic proposal and outline in the JVNA's newsletter, along with a statement that Lionel Friedberg was willing to make the film for "a very low fee, basically to cover his costs".
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-sacred-duty] The film was funded by the JVNA through private contributions.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-sacred-duty] Preliminary drafts of the script were circulated among members of the JVNA advisory committee and others for input, after which the script went through numerous revisions.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-sacred-duty] Meanwhile, Schwartz and Friedberg set about interviewing possible participants and filming footage of nature in both Israel and the United States.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-sacred-duty] The showing of slaughterhouse footage was controversial, with some members of a test audience in Staten Island seeing it as propaganda.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-sacred-duty] Friedberg recalled, "Richard and I were accused of making a propaganda film for the vegetarian movement.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-sacred-duty] We were accused of showing 'horrors that are impossible to watch'." However, he maintained that the graphic footage was necessary.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-sacred-duty] In October and November 2007, *A Sacred Duty* was released direct-to-video and on DVD, with public showings in both Israel and the United States.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-sacred-duty] Over 35,000 copies were distributed free of charge to synagogues, educational institutions, and individuals, complete with permission to show the film without having to pay the filmmakers any royalties.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-sacred-duty] In addition, permission was granted to the public to duplicate and distribute the film free of charge.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-sacred-duty] Numerous short excerpts from the film were edited and re-posted by various YouTube users, and the full version became available on YouTube in January 2008.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] It is a foundational essay advocating for vegetarianism, maintaining that a plant-based diet is essential for bodily health, moral virtue, and social justice.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley argued that meat consumption is unnatural, a "slow but certain poison", causing disease, which "pollutes" the body, and leads to vice and depravity.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He prescribes the return to a "natural" vegetable diet.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] This work is regarded as one of the earliest and most fervent defenses of vegetarianism in English literature.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley wrote four essays on the subject of vegetarianism, "A Vindication of Natural Diet" (1813), the note in *Queen Mab*, in a section of "A Refutation of Deism" (1814), and "On the Vegetable System of Diet", which was published posthumously in 1929.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley first experimented with a vegetarian diet while at the University of Oxford according to Thomas Jefferson Hogg.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley began a vegetarian diet on 1 March 1812 along with his first wife Harriet Westbrook.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley began composing the essay in October–November 1812.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley met John Frank Newton during 1812-1813 and influenced his views on vegetarianism.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Historian Keith Thomas has noted that Newton's *Return to Nature* "provided much of the basis" for Shelley's *A Vindication of Natural Diet*.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The work has been republished since 1813, beginning with an abridged version which was published in Boston by March, Capen, and Lyon in an American collection *Vegetable Diet: As Sanctioned by Medical Men, and by Experience in All Ages*, edited by William A.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The essay was reprinted in 1884 in a new edition in London by Frederick Pitman and by John Heywood and the Vegetarian Society in Manchester.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The original title page was reproduced: *A Vindication of Natural Diet.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Being One in a Series of Notes to Queen Mab (A Philosophical Poem).* London: Printed for J.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The new edition featured a preface by Henry Stephens Salt and William Axon.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In 1904, the work was republished in London by C.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Daniel as *A Vindication of Natural Diet and Extracts from the Works of Dr.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley used the imagery of slaughtering a lamb.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In the novel *Frankenstein; or, The Modern Prometheus* (1818), which he is acknowledged to have contributed to, the Being is portrayed as a vegetarian.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The Being explained his vegetarian diet to Victor Frankenstein: "My food is not that of man.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] I do not destroy the lamb and the kid to glut my appetite; acorns and berries afford me sufficient nourishment." Shelley's views on vegetarianism are routinely incorrectly attributed to his wife.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In *Laon and Cythna*, republished as *The Revolt of Islam* (1817), Fifth Canto, the Festival of nations held after the Revolution is a banquet where no meat is served.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The feast is vegetarian: "Never again may blood of bird or beast/ Stain with its venomous stream a human feast".
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] This is "The banquet of the free" where the guests are described as "reclining as they ate, of Liberty,/ And Hope, and Justice".
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The festival was not polluted by gore, "But piled on high, an overflowing store/ Of pomegranates, and citrons, fairest fruit,/ Melons, and dates, and figs, and many a root".
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley argued that eating meat was unnatural.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He maintained that diseases and immorality arose from mankind's "unnatural habits of life".
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] A meatless diet was the best regimen for maintaining a healthy and disease-free lifestyle.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He wrote that human diseases could be decreased by a return to a natural vegetable diet.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley argued that eating meat was a practice that polluted the body with syphilis and resulted in other ailments.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In *A Vindication of Natural Diet* he wrote, "Should ever a physician be born with the genius of Locke, I am persuaded that he might trace all bodily and mental derangements to our unnatural habits," these unnatural habits being the consumption of meat.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He cited the allegory of Prometheus who stole fire from the gods which enabled mankind to cook meat, thereby screening the disgust and horror of dead flesh.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He concluded that a person with compassion and empathy for animals, "rising from a meal of roots", would be able to maintain a healthy and balanced diet and lifestyle.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley presented examples of how a vegetarian diet resulted in longevity and an increased lifespan.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The only threat of death will be that of natural, old age, that "old age would be our last and our only malady".
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The two rules he prescribes for a natural diet are to never eat anything that was alive and to drink only distilled water.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] The word *Ahimsa*—sometimes spelled *Ahinsa*—derives from the Sanskrit root *hiṃs*, meaning to strike; *hiṃsā* is injury or harm, while *a-hiṃsā* (prefixed with the alpha privative), its opposite, is *non-harming* or *nonviolence*.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Reverence for *ahimsa* can be found in Jain, Hindu, and Buddhist canonical texts.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Lord Parshvanatha (the 23rd of Jainism's 24 Tirthankaras) is said to have preached *ahimsa* as one of the four vows.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Scholars describe nonviolence as a central doctrinal and practical principle of Jainism, developed to an extent that distinguishes it from most other religious traditions of the Indian subcontinent.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] 1500 BCE) is the oldest surviving text in India, but many scholars believe the specific ethical practice of *ahimsa* originated in the non-Vedic *Sramana* traditions (which include Jainism and Buddhism) before being absorbed into Brahmanism.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Deshmukh, suggest that the roots of *ahimsa* and asceticism may date to the Indus Valley Civilisation (c.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] 3300–1300 BCE), citing the discovery of seals depicting figures in the *kayotsarga* (standing meditation) posture common to Jain iconography.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Indologist Johannes Bronkhorst has proposed the "Greater Magadha" theory, arguing that the eastern Gangetic plain (modern Bihar/Bengal) developed a distinct non-Vedic culture where concepts like *Karma*, rebirth, and *ahimsa* originated.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] According to this view, the Vedic priesthood later adopted these concepts as they expanded eastward.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Similarly, the German Indologist Ludwig Alsdorf argued that *ahimsa* likely began not as a moral rule but as a "magico-ritualistic" taboo against killing or harming living beings, which was part of a pan-Indian or pre-Aryan heritage later refined into an ethical system by the Jains.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] The concept of *ahimsa* evolved gradually within the Vedic tradition.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] 1500–1000 BCE), animal sacrifice was a central component of ritual life.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Then the concept transitioned from a ritualistic concern-avoiding injury to the sacrificer or the minute details of the ritual—to an internalized ethical virtue.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] By the late Vedic era, texts like the *Chandogya Upanishad* (c.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] 8th century BCE) explicitly listed *ahimsa* as one of five essential virtues (along with truthfulness and charity).
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] The *Yajurveda* reflects this shifting ethos with prayers for universal peace, such as: "May all beings look at me with a friendly eye, may I do likewise, and may we look at each other with the eyes of a friend".
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] The principle of *ahimsa* moved from personal asceticism to state policy under the Mauryan Emperor Ashoka (c.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Following the Kalinga War, Ashoka renounced military conquest in favor of "conquest by Dharma".
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] His Rock Edicts restricted animal slaughter, established medical care for animals, and promoted nonviolence as a civic duty, embedding the Shramanic value of *ahimsa* into India's political fabric.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] In Jainism, the understanding and implementation of *ahimsa* is more radical, scrupulous, and comprehensive than in any other religion.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Killing any living being out of passions like attachment is considered *hiṃsā* (to injure) and abstaining from such an act is *ahimsā* (noninjury).
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] The vow of *ahimsā* is considered the foremost among the "five vows of Jainism".
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Other vows like truth (*satya*) are meant for safeguarding the vow of *ahimsā*.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] The statement *ahimsā paramo dharmaḥ* (or, "Non-injury/nonviolence/harmlessness is the supreme/ultimate/paramount/highest/absolute duty/virtue/attribute/religion") is often found inscribed on the walls of the Jain temples.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] As in Hinduism, the aim is to prevent the accumulation of harmful karma.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] The Jain concept of *ahimsa* is characterised by detailed classifications of life.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Jains categorize living beings (*jiva*) based on their sensory faculties (*indriyas*), ranging from one-sensed beings (plants, water, earth) to five-sensed beings (humans, animals).
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Killing of animals for food is absolutely ruled out.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Jains also make considerable efforts not to injure plants in everyday life as far as possible.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Though they admit that plants must be destroyed for the sake of food, they accept such violence only inasmuch as it is indispensable for human survival, and there are special instructions for preventing unnecessary violence against plants.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Jain monks and nuns go out of their way so as not to hurt even small insects and other minuscule animals.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Both the renouncers and the laypeople of Jain faith reject meat, fish, alcohol, and honey as these are believed to harm large or minuscule life forms.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] In the practice of *ahimsa*, the requirements are less strict for the lay persons (*sravakas*) who have undertaken *anuvrata* (Smaller Vows) than for the Jain monastics who are bound by the Mahavrata "Great Vows".
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Jain scholars have debated the potential injury to other life forms during one's occupation.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Certain Jain texts (according to Padmanabh Jaini, a Jainism scholar) forbid people of its faith from husbandry, agriculture, and trade in animal-derived products.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Some Jains abstain from farming because it inevitably entails unintentional killing or injuring of many small animals, such as worms and insects.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] These teachings, in part, have led the Jain community to focus on trade, merchant, clerical, and administrative occupations to minimize *arambhaja-himsa* (occupational violence against all life forms).
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] For the layperson, the teaching has been of *ahimsa* with *pramada* – that is, reducing violence through proper intention and being careful in every action on a daily basis to minimize violence to all life forms.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] When Mahavira revived and reorganised the Jain faith in the 6th or 5th century BCE, *ahimsa* was already an established, strictly observed rule.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Rishabhanatha (Ādinātha), the first Jain Tirthankara, whom modern Western historians consider to be a historical figure, followed by Parshvanatha (Pārśvanātha) the twenty-third Tirthankara lived in about the 9th century BCE.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] He founded the community to which Mahavira's parents belonged.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Ahimsa was already part of the "Fourfold Restraint" (*Caujjama*), the vows taken by Parshva's followers.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] In the times of Mahavira and in the following centuries, Jains were at odds with both Buddhists and followers of the Vedic religion or Hindus, whom they accused of negligence and inconsistency in the implementation of *ahimsa*.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] According to the Jain tradition either lacto vegetarianism or veganism is prescribed.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] The Jain texts, unlike most Hindu and Buddhist texts on just war, have been inconsistent.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] For its monastic community – *sadhu* and *sadhvi* – the historically accepted practice has been to "willingly sacrifice one's own life" to the attacker, to not retaliate, so that the mendicant may keep the First Great Vow of "total nonviolence".
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Jain literature of the 10th century CE, for example, describes a king ready for war and being given lessons about non-violence by the Jain acharya (spiritual teacher).
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] In the 12th century CE and thereafter, in an era of violent raids, destruction of temples, the slaughter of agrarian communities and ascetics by Islamic armies, Jain scholars reconsidered the First Great Vow of mendicants and its parallel for the laypeople.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] The medieval texts of this era, such as by Jinadatta Suri, recommended both the mendicants and the laypeople to fight and kill if that would prevent greater and continued violence on humans and other life forms (*virodhi-himsa*).
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Such exemptions to *ahimsa* is a relatively rare teaching in Jain texts, states Dundas.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Mahatma Gandhi stated, "No religion in the World has explained the principle of *Ahiṃsā* so deeply and systematically as is discussed with its applicability in every human life in Jainism.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] As and when the benevolent principle of *Ahiṃsā* or non-violence will be ascribed for practice by the people of the world to achieve their end of life in this world and beyond, Jainism is sure to have the uppermost status and Mahāvīra is sure to be respected as the greatest authority on *Ahiṃsā*".
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] The term *Ahimsa* appears in the text Taittiriya Shakha of the Yajurveda (TS 5.2.8.7), where it refers to non-injury to the sacrificer.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] It occurs several times in the *Shatapatha Brahmana* in the sense of "non-injury".
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] The *Ahimsa* doctrine is a late Vedic era development in Brahmanical culture.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] The earliest reference to the idea of nonviolence to animals (*pashu-Ahimsa*), apparently in a moral sense, is in the Kapisthala Katha Samhita of the Yajurveda (KapS 31.11), which may have been written around 1500-1200 BCE.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] The Chandogya Upanishad (3.17.4) includes ahimsa in its list of virtues.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] According to John Bowker, the word appears but is uncommon in the principal Upanishads.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Kaneda gives examples of the word *pashu-Ahimsa* in these Upanishads.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Other scholars suggest *Ahimsa* as an ethical concept started evolving in the Vedas, becoming an increasingly central concept in the Upanishads.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] The Chāndogya Upaniṣad, dated to 800 to 600 BCE, one of the oldest Upanishads, has the earliest evidence of Vedic use of the word *Ahimsa* in the sense familiar in Hinduism (a code of conduct).
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] It bars violence against "all creatures" (*sarvabhuta*), and the practitioner of *Ahimsa* is said to escape the cycle of rebirths (CU 8.15.1).
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Some scholars say this mention may have been a Jainist influence on Vedic Hinduism.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Others scholar say that is speculative, and though Jainism is an ancient tradition, the oldest traceable texts of Jainism are from many centuries after the Vedic era ended.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Chāndogya Upaniṣad also names *Ahimsa*, along with *Satyavacanam* (truthfulness), *Ārjavam* (sincerity), *Dānam* (charity), and *Tapo* (penance/meditation), as one of five essential virtues (CU 3.17.4).
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] The Sandilya Upanishad lists ten forbearances: *Ahimsa*, *Satya*, *Asteya*, *Brahmacharya*, *Daya*, *Arjava*, *Kshama*, *Dhriti*, *Mitahara*, and *Saucha*.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] According to Kaneda, the term *Ahimsa* is an important spiritual doctrine shared by Hinduism, Buddhism, and Jainism.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] It means 'non-injury' and 'non-killing'.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] It implies total avoidance of harming any living creature by deeds, words, or thoughts.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] The Hindu epic the Mahabharata repeatedly uses the phrase *Ahimsa Paramo Dharma* (अहिंसा परमॊ धर्मः), which literally means "nonviolence is the highest moral virtue".
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] The phrase *Ahimsa Paramo Dharma* also appears in Adi Parva, Vana Parva, and Anushasana Parva.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] The Bhagavad Gita discusses doubts and questions about appropriate response when one faces systematic violence or war.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] These verses develop the concepts of lawful violence in self-defence and just war theory.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] But there is no consensus on this interpretation.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Gandhi, for example, considered this debate about nonviolence and lawful violence a mere metaphor for the war within a human being when they face moral questions.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] The classical texts of Hinduism devote numerous chapters to discussing what people who practice the virtue of *ahimsa* can and must do when faced with war, violent threat, or the need to sentence someone convicted of a crime.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] These discussions have led to theories of just war, ideas of reasonable self-defense, and views of proportionate punishment.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Arthashastra discusses, among other things, what constitutes proportionate response and punishment.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] The precepts of *ahimsa* in Hinduism require that war must be avoided, with sincere and truthful dialogue.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] If war becomes necessary, its cause must be just, its purpose virtuous, its objective to restrain the wicked, its aim peace, and its method lawful.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] War may be started and stopped only by a legitimate authority.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Weapons must be proportionate to the opponent and the goal, not indiscriminate tools of destruction.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] All strategies and weapons used in war must be to defeat the opponent, not to cause them misery; for example, arrows are allowed, but arrows smeared with painful poison are not.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Warriors must use judgment in the battlefield.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Wounded, unarmed opponents must not be attacked or killed but instead given medical care.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Children, women, and civilians must not be injured.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] While the war is in progress, sincere dialogue for peace must continue.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Different interpretations of ancient Hindu texts have been offered in matters of self-defense.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] For example, Tähtinen suggests self-defense is appropriate, criminals are not protected by the rule of *ahimsa*, and Hindu scriptures support violence against an armed attacker.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] *ahimsa* is not meant to imply pacifism.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Alternative theories of self-defense, inspired by *ahimsa*, build principles similar to ideas of just war.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Aikido, pioneered in Japan, illustrates one such set of principles for self-defense.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Morihei Ueshiba, the founder of Aikido, described his inspiration as Ahimsa.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] According to this interpretation of *ahimsa* in self-defense, one must not assume that the world is free of aggression.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] One must presume that some people will, out of ignorance, error, or fear, attack others or intrude into their space, physically or verbally.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] The aim of self-defense, suggested Ueshiba, must be to neutralize the attacker's aggression and avoid conflict.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] The best defense is one with which the victim is protected and the attacker is respected and not injured if possible.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Under *ahimsa* and Aikido, there are no enemies, and appropriate self-defense focuses on neutralizing the immaturity, assumptions, and aggressive strivings of the attacker.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Tähtinen concludes that Hindus have no misgivings about the death penalty; their position is that evil-doers who deserve death should be killed and that a king, in particular, is obliged to punish criminals and should not hesitate to kill them, even if they happen to be his brothers and sons.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Other scholars conclude that Hindu scriptures suggest that sentences for any crime must be fair, proportional, and not cruel.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] The Hindu precept of "cause no injury" applies to animals and all life forms.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] This precept is not found in the oldest verses of Vedas (1500–1000 BCE), but increasingly becomes one of the central ideas in post-Vedic period.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] In the oldest layer of the Vedas, such as the *Rigveda*, ritual sacrifices of animals and cooking of meat to feed guests are mentioned.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] This included goat, ox, horse, and others.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] However, the text is not uniform in its prescriptions.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Some verses praise meat as food, while other verses in the Vedas recommend "abstention from meat", in particular, "beef".
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] According to Marvin Harris, the Vedic literature is inconsistent, with some verses suggesting ritual slaughter and meat consumption, while others suggesting a taboo on meat-eating.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] The late Vedic-era literature (pre-500 BCE) condemns all killings of men, cattle, birds, and horses, and prays to god Agni to punish those who kill.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Later texts of Hinduism declare *ahimsa* as one of the primary virtues, declare any killing or harming any life as against *dharma* (moral life).
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] The Mahabharata permits hunting by warriors, but opposes it in the case of hermits who must be strictly non-violent.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Across the texts of Hinduism, there is a profusion of ideas about the virtue of *ahimsa* when applied to non-human life, but without a universal consensus.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Alsdorf claims the debate and disagreements between supporters of vegetarian lifestyle and meat eaters was significant.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Even suggested exceptions – ritual slaughter and hunting – were challenged by advocates of *ahimsa*.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] In the Mahabharata both sides present various arguments to substantiate their viewpoints.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Moreover, a hunter defends his profession in a long discourse.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Many of the arguments proposed in favor of non-violence to animals refer to the bliss one feels, the rewards it entails before or after death, the danger and harm it prevents, as well as to the karmic consequences of violence.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] The ancient Hindu texts discuss *ahimsa* and non-animal life.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] They discourage wanton destruction of nature including of wild and cultivated plants.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Hermits (sannyasins) were urged to live on a fruitarian diet so as to avoid the destruction of plants.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Scholars claim the principles of ecological nonviolence are innate in the Hindu tradition, and its conceptual fountain has been *ahimsa* as its cardinal virtue.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] The classical literature of the Indian religions, such as Hinduism and Jainism, exists in many Indian languages.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] For example, the *Tirukkural,* written in three volumes, likely between 450 and 500 CE, dedicates verses 251–260 and 321–333 of its first volume to the virtue of *ahimsa*, emphasizing on moral vegetarianism and non-killing (*kollamai*).
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] However, the *Tirukkural* also glorifies soldiers and their valour during war, and states that it is king's duty to punish criminals and implement "death sentence for the wicked".
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Jay Dinshah founded the American Vegan Society (AVS), linking veganism to the concept of *ahimsa*.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] In the 19th and 20th centuries, prominent figures of Indian spirituality such as Shrimad Rajchandra and Swami Vivekananda emphasised the importance of Ahimsa.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Mohandas Karamchand Gandhi successfully promoted the principle of *ahimsa* to all spheres of life, in particular to politics (*Swaraj*).
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] His non-violent resistance movement *satyagraha* had an immense impact on India, impressed public opinion in Western countries, and influenced the leaders of various civil and political rights movements such as the American civil rights movement's Martin Luther King Jr. and James Bevel.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] In Gandhi's thought, *ahimsa* precludes not only the act of inflicting a physical injury but also mental states like evil thoughts and hatred, and unkind behavior such as harsh words, dishonesty, and lying, all of which he saw as manifestations of violence incompatible with *ahimsa*.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Gandhi believed *ahimsa* to be a creative energy force, encompassing all interactions leading one's self to find *satya*, "Divine Truth".
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Sri Aurobindo criticized the Gandhian concept of *ahimsa* as unrealistic and not universally applicable, noting that while it is a spiritual truth, it should not be applied as a "rigid ethical rule" to all of humanity.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] He adopted a pragmatic non-pacifist position, holding that the justification of violence depends on the specific circumstances and the "dharma" (duty/righteousness) of the situation.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] While he advocated passive resistance as a political policy for India's independence, he maintained that a nation is entitled to use violence for its self-preservation if necessary.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Gandhi took the religious principle of *ahimsa,* and turned it into a non-violent tool for mass action.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] He used it to fight not only colonial rule, but social evils such as racial discrimination and untouchability as well.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Studying *ahimsa*'s history and philosophy influenced Albert Schweitzer's principle of "reverence for life".
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] He commended Indian traditions for their ethics of *ahimsa*, considering the prohibition against killing and harming "one of the greatest events in the spiritual history of humankind".
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] However, he noted that "not-killing" and "not-harming" might be unfeasible in certain situations, like self-defense, or ethically complex, as in cases of prolonged famine.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] In Buddhist texts *ahimsa* (or its Pāli cognate *avihiṃsā*) is part of the Five Precepts (*Pañcasīla*), the first of which has been to abstain from killing.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] This precept of *ahimsa* is applicable to both the Buddhist layperson and the monastic community.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] The *ahimsa* precept is not a commandment, and transgressions did not invite religious sanctions for laypersons, but their power has been in the Buddhist belief in karmic consequences and their impact in afterlife during rebirth.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Killing, in Buddhist belief, could lead to rebirth in the hellish realm, and for a longer time in more severe conditions if the murder victim was a monk.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Saving animals from slaughter for meat is believed to be a way to acquire merit for better rebirth.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] These moral precepts have been voluntarily self-enforced in lay Buddhist culture through the associated belief in karma and rebirth.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Unlike with lay Buddhists, transgressions by monks do invite sanctions.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Full expulsion of a monk from *sangha* follows instances of killing, just like any other serious offense against the monastic *nikaya* code of conduct.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Violent ways of punishing criminals and prisoners of war were not explicitly condemned in Buddhism, but peaceful ways of conflict resolution and punishment with the least amount of injury were encouraged.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] The early texts condemn the mental states that lead to violent behavior.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Nonviolence is an overarching theme within the Pāli Canon.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] While the early texts condemn killing in the strongest terms, and portray the ideal ruler as a pacifist, such a ruler is nonetheless flanked by an army.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] It seems that the Buddha's teaching on nonviolence was not interpreted or put into practice in an uncompromisingly pacifist or anti-military service way by early Buddhists.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] The early texts assume war to be a fact of life, and well-skilled soldiers are viewed as necessary for defensive warfare.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] In Pali texts, injunctions to abstain from violence and involvement with military affairs are directed at members of the *sangha*; later Mahayana texts, which often generalise monastic norms to laity, require this of lay people as well.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] The early texts do not contain just-war ideology as such.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Some argue that a *sutta* in the *Gamani Samyuttam* rules out all military service.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] In this passage, a soldier asks the Buddha if it is true that, as he has been told, soldiers slain in battle are reborn in a heavenly realm.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] The Buddha reluctantly replies that if he is killed in battle while his mind is seized with the intention to kill, he will undergo an unpleasant rebirth.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] In the early texts, a person's mental state at the time of death is generally viewed as having a great impact on the next birth.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Some Buddhists point to other early texts as justifying defensive war.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] One example is the *Kosala Samyutta*, in which King Pasenadi of Kosala, a righteous king favored by the Buddha, learns of an impending attack on his kingdom.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] He arms himself in defence, and leads his army into battle to protect his kingdom from attack.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] King Pasenadi eventually defeated Emperor Ajātasattu and captured him alive.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] He thought that, although this King of Magadha has transgressed against his kingdom, he had not transgressed against him personally, and Ajātasattu was still his nephew.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] He released Ajātasattu and did not harm him.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Upon his return, the Buddha said (among other things) that Pasenadi "is a friend of virtue, acquainted with virtue, intimate with virtue", while the opposite is said of the aggressor, King Ajātasattu.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] According to Theravada commentaries, there are five requisite factors that must all be fulfilled for an act to be both an act of killing and to be karmically negative.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] These are: (1) the presence of a living being, human or animal; (2) the knowledge that the being is a living being; (3) the intent to kill; (4) the act of killing by some means; and (5) the resulting death.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Some Buddhists have argued on this basis that the act of killing is complicated, and its ethicality is predicated upon intent.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Some have argued that in defensive postures, for example, the primary intention of a soldier is not to kill, but to defend against aggression, and the act of killing in that situation would have minimal negative karmic repercussions.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] According to Babasaheb Ambedkar, there is circumstantial evidence encouraging *ahimsa* from the Buddha's doctrine, "Love all, so that you may not wish to kill any." Gautama Buddha distinguished between a principle and a rule.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] He did not make *ahimsa* a matter of rule, but suggested it as a matter of principle.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Maurya Emperor Ashoka banned animal sacrifice, hunting, slaughter of "all four-footed creatures that are neither useful nor edible" and specific animal species, female goats, sheep and pigs nursing their young as well as their young up to the age of six months.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Fishing was banned during Chaturmasya and Uposatha.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Slave trade in the Maurya Empire was also banned by Ashoka.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] The emperors of the Sui dynasty, Tang dynasty, and early Song dynasty banned killing in the Lunar calendar's 1st, 5th, and 9th months.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Empress Wu Tse-Tien banned killing for more than half a year in 692.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] Some rulers banned fishing for a period of time each year.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/ahimsa] People avoid killing during some festivals, like the Taoist Ghost Festival, the Nine Emperor Gods Festival, and the Vegetarian Festival, as well as during others.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/elizabeth-s-gone-raw] The restaurant opened as an "occasional restaurant" in July 2010 on the second floor of a row house, serving three Friday nights per month.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/elizabeth-s-gone-raw] In September 2018 it added Saturday night service.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/elizabeth-s-gone-raw] It serves only a prix fixe seven-course tasting menu.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/elizabeth-s-gone-raw] In addition to being vegan, much of the food is also raw.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/elizabeth-s-gone-raw] The restaurant and its menu have been favorably reviewed and widely praised.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/elizabeth-s-gone-raw] *Food & Wine* listed it as one of 19 best vegetarian and vegan restaurants in the US.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/elizabeth-s-gone-raw] *The Washington Post* called it "an upscale vegan dinner party." *Washington Life* magazine called the vegan tasting menu a masterpiece.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/elizabeth-s-gone-raw] Food Network named them one of the top 20 vegan restaurants in the United States.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/elizabeth-s-gone-raw] In 2024, then-Washington Wizards offensive coach Joseph Blair said Elizabeth's was one of his favorite Washington, D.C. area restaurants.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/elizabeth-s-gone-raw] In 2019, Big 7 Travel named it one of 50 best vegan-friendly restaurants in the world.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/elizabeth-s-gone-raw] In 2018 Eater named it the best vegan restaurant in D.C. and *Modern Farmer* named it one of the 15 best vegan restaurants in the US.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/elizabeth-s-gone-raw] In 2017 the *Evening Standard* named it one of the 18 best vegan restaurants in the world and Tasting Table named it one of the eight best vegan restaurants in the US.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/elizabeth-s-gone-raw] In 2015 PETA named them one of the six best vegan fine-dining restaurants in the U.S. and BuzzFeed named it one of 24 "bucket list" vegan restaurants.
[src:elizabeth-s-gone-raw/elizabeth-s-gone-raw] In 2014 *Relish* named it one of the 15 best vegan and vegetarian restaurants in the U.S.
